04596nam a22008055i 9780231520348DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012035759  a97802315203487 a10.7312/taub154122doi  a(DE-B1597)459375  a(OCoLC)979575023  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC263.T38bA4 2013 4aJC263.T38bA4 2015 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.5330922231 aTaubes, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTo Carl Schmitt :bLetters and Reflections /cJacob Taubes. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: “A Very Rare Thing” -- tApocalyptic Prophet of the Counterrevolution -- tLetter to Armin Mohler -- tAppendix. Four Passages from Letters of Carl Schmitt to Armin Mohler -- tLetter to Carl Schmitt -- tExtract from a Dispute About Carl Schmitt -- t1948–1978. Thirty Years of Refusal -- tEditorial Note -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA philosopher, rabbi, religious historian, and Gnostic, Jacob Taubes was for many years a correspondent and interlocutor of Carl Schmitt (1888–1985), a German jurist, philosopher, political theorist, law professor—and self-professed Nazi. Despite their unlikely association, Taubes and Schmitt shared an abiding interest in the fundamental problems of political theology, believing the great challenges of modern political theory were ancient in pedigree and, in many cases, anticipated the works of Judeo-Christian eschatologists. In this collection of Taubes's writings on Schmitt, the two intellectuals work through ideas of the apocalypse and other central concepts of political theology. Taubes acknowledges Schmitt's reservations about the weakness of liberal democracy yet distances himself from his prescription to rectify it, arguing the apocalyptic worldview requires less of a rigid hierarchical social ordering than a community committed to the importance of decision making. In these writings, a sharper and more nuanced portrait of Schmitt's thought emerges, as well as a more complicated understanding of Taubes, who has shaped the work of Giorgio Agamben, Peter Sloterdijk, and other major twentieth-century theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiography as a literary formvFiction. 0aFathers and sonsvFiction. 0aJewszOntariovFiction. 0aPolitical scientistszGermanyvCorrespondence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aGente, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimshaw, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimshaw, Mike.1 aSchmitt, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTribe, Keith.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/taub1541240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231520348.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK